manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Republic of Gamers (ROG), part of the ASUS family, is dedicated to creating innovative hardcore gaming hardware for gamers. ROG is committed to providing the absolute best performance and quality from its complete line of products. ROG is for those keen on the finest gaming hardware and software as it enables the ultimate computing experience for gamers and enthusiasts worldwide. It incorporates a stylish gamer-focused design, merging the excitement of gaming with a unique premium style. ROG MAXIMUS Z790 HERO ASUS ROG Maximus Z790 Hero Intel Z790 LGA 1700 ATX motherboard, 20 + 1 power stages, DDR5, five M.2 slots, PCIe 5.0, Thunderbolt 4 USB Type-C port, WiFi 6E, AI Overclocking, and Aura Sync RGB Intel LGA 1700 socket: Ready for 13th Gen Intel Core processors & 12th Gen Intel Core, Pentium Gold and Celeron Processors Robust Power Solution: 20 + 1 teamed power solution rated for 90A per stage with dual ProCool II power connectors, high-quality alloy chokes, and durable capacitors to support multi-core processors Optimized VRM Thermals: Massive heatsinks integrated with the I/O cover, joined by an L-shaped heatpipe, and connected to the power stages with high-conductivity thermal pads Next-Gen M.2 Support: PCIe 5.0 M.2 slot on the bundled ROG Hyper M.2 card, and four PCIe 4.0 M.2 slots all with substantial cooling solutions Connectivity: Dual Thunderbolt 4 USB Type-C ports, USB 3.2 Gen 2x2 Type-C front-panel connector with Quick Charge 4+ up to 60W, six additional USB 3.2 Gen 2 ports, two PCIe 5.0 x16 SafeSlots, HDMI 2.1 High-Performance Networking: On-board Intel WIFI 6E (802.11ax) and Intel 2.5 Gb Ethernet with ASUS LANGuard Intelligent Control: ASUS-exclusive AI Overclocking, AI Cooling II, AI Networking and Two-Way AI Noise Cancelation to simplify setup and improve performance

AI OVERCLOCKING Tuning is now faster and smarter than ever before. ASUS AI Overclocking profiles the CPU and cooling to predict the optimal configuration and push the system to its limits. Predicted values can be engaged automatically or used as a launching ground for further experimentation. TEAMED POWER ARCHITECTURE Today's CPU architectures place incredible demands on motherboard power design by transitioning from deep power-saving modes, going from lower-power mode to full load in an instant. The latest ROG VRM architecture rises to the challenge by utilizing teamed power stages to rapidly swing current, while maintaining exemplary thermal performance. MEMORY ROG has a long legacy of flexing the fastest memory performance, and DDR5 is no outlier. Thanks to improved signal routing, now enthusiast-grade kits have been driven far beyond the 7 GT/s mark on the Maximus Z790 Hero, and who knows how far future DIMMs can go? Seasoned veterans can test their mettle by tinkering with the extensive array of tuning options in the UEFI.

COOLER BY DESIGN 1. VRM and aluminum I/O heatsink: A VRM heatsink on the MOSFETs and chokes is connected to the aluminum I/O cover via an embedded heatpipe to increase mass and surface area for dissipation. 2. High-conductivity thermal pads: Each thermal pad improves overall heat transfer from the system by bridging the heat generated by the power stages to the heatsink. For future maintenance, a replacement thermal pad can also be found in the package. Solid steel backplate: A plate of electro-galvanized steel strengthens the spine of the ROG Maximus Z790 Hero to prevent bending. 3. Chipset heatsink: A dedicated heatsink draws heat away from the chipset to maintain optimum operating temperature. 4. M.2 heatsink and backplates: Large aluminum heatsinks provide extensive surface area to cool mounted M.2 drives, and each of the three onboard slots has a dedicated backplate for additional heat dissipation. PCIE 5.0 STORAGE ROG HYPER M.2 CARD Two additional slots ride on the ROG Hyper M.2 Card, providing the option to deploy both a PCIe 5.0 and 4.0 drive under a large heatsink that ensures optimal temperatures. PCIE 5.0 EXPANSION SLOTS Both of the x16 expansion slots have the PCIe 5.0 treatment to offer incredible speeds up to 64 GB/s for compatible devices. To bear the brunt of massive graphics cards, they are also protected with SafeSlot retention brackets, and the top slot can be released easily thanks to the Q-Release button.

NETWORKING WIFI 6E Onboard WiFi 6E technology takes advantage of newly available spectrum in the 6 GHz band to provide up to seven 160 MHz channels for ultrafast throughput and better performance in dense wireless environments. 2.5G ETHERNET Low-latency gaming, speedy file transfers, and high-resolution video streaming are among the many perks of onboard Intel 2.5 Gbps Ethernet. SUPREMEFX ROG SupremeFX audio technology delivers an exceptional 113 dB signal-to-noise ratio on the line-in connection to provide exceptional recording quality. There’s also a low-dropout regulator for cleaner power delivery to the SupremeFX ALC4082 codec, and an integrated ESS ES9218 QUAD DAC capable of reaching -115dB THD+N for superior front-panel output. The combined solution allows for end-to-end 32-bit 384 kHz resolution playback that conveys all the subtlety and nuances of each audio track. GROW YOUR GAMING WORLD WITH AURA SYNC Up your game with complementary Aura Sync enhanced aesthetics, featuring preset lighting effects that can be easily synchronized across compatible ROG graphics cards, monitors, keyboards, and mice to give your setup a unified look.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 22, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A bit too expensive for the features
reviews.reviewText: For the most part this is a great motherboard, and it **** well better be at a $600 price point. Tons of thunderbolt, usb-c,usb 3 ports, wired antenna (though they switched to a much easier to use wifi antenna on the model immediately after this), great XMP support, same Asus bios as expected, Armory Crate and AI Suite are great (though for some reason AI Suite doens't work when Memory Protection is turned on), TPM support, 4 NVME connectors but that's where things start to suck.The only PCIE5 NVME slots "on" this board are actually on the PCIE expansion card, which is a complete waste for anyone who intends to use anything besides a GPU given there are only two PCIE slots.I cannot stress this enough - if you have any intention of using the onboard Intel Bluetooth adapter, you have to use the wifi antenna provided. The bluetooth adapter is absolute garbage without it. It took 3 hours of trying to understand why the connection was barely functional compared to a USB adapter with no antenna and thats why. Antenna is not optional.This motherboard will also cause tons of kernel crashes and other hardware IRQ issues until you finally install all the drivers and Windows updates, so good luck with that.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on June 7, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A wonderful motherboard with great features, but DDR 5 memory support is still spotty.
reviews.reviewText: I upgraded my PC from a Z590 Hero to this Z790 Hero, and I couldn't be more pleased... except for the lack of broad DDR 5 memory support. I tried a 4-stick 128GB Kingston DDR 5 Kit that was supposedly supported but found it very unstable. I fell back to a 2-stick 64GB Corsair kit that has been rock-solid.Otherwise, the board has many wonderful features and is easy to use. The BIOS is easy to work with and has its own manual you must read before you start your build. Certain defaults aren't trivial, and I've seen many folks freak out in the ASUS forum and blame ASUS for it. Not so!I highly recommend this motherboard.One caveat: installing Windows 11 needs attention, as the 22H2 USB doesn't contain the required LAN drivers, effectively stopping the installation. You need to prepare a separate USB stick with the drivers you can download from the ASUS site and load them during installation.Disclaimer: I am receiving a warranty extension from ASUS for my feedback.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on August 31, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Beautiful, well designed Motherboard, quite overpriced
reviews.reviewText: Those looking for a high-end motherboard, Asus ROG Hero is a no brainer. It has all the standard high-end motherboard features like 20 power phase, japanese capacitors, etc etc.I just purchase it because its what I had always bought in the past - Asus ROG Hero 7 and Asus ROG Crosshair 4. It just works and is aesthetically pleasing to the eye. Comes with a 3 year warranty - online registration required.It's overpriced compared to ROG motherboards of the past. Motherboards never costed more than the CPU back in the day. Now, it's more than the CPU - crazy.......

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 5, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Great little board minus audio
reviews.reviewText: This is a great little board that handles all of today's gaming demands. My only gripe about this board is the audio chip used. It has two real problems with it. First, if you use a Logitech (or similar) 5.1 or 7.1 surround audio system, don't use the onboard audio. The physical cables (including fiber optic) don't map correctly and you won't have rear and bass channels. Second, the sonic application used to in windows 11 is absolutely garbage. If you just run the app for more than 2-3 minutes and are tweaking things, it basically locks not only the application up, but the hardware audio chip as well. You end up having to power the board completely off to get audio back. After some googling, I find that this is a known issue with this audio chip and that Asus is working on it, but so far no luck. Outside of the audio, everything else runs great. Nice and compact and I run all of the NVMe slots and it was easy to setup and use. If your running a 4000 series nvidia card, realize your going to lose out on the second PCI slot, it's exposed, but nothing will fit. This is expected with such big graphics cards now.
